Here's a recommended structure for testing C# MCP server tools without hitting the real API:

**1. Abstract the HTTP dependency**

```csharp
// In your server project
public interface IMyApiClient
{
    Task<ResultDto> GetDataAsync(string id);
}

public class MyApiClient : IMyApiClient
{
    private readonly HttpClient _http;
    public MyApiClient(HttpClient http) => _http = http;
    public async Task<ResultDto> GetDataAsync(string id) =>
        await _http.GetFromJsonAsync<ResultDto>($"/api/data/{id}");
}
```

**2. Inject the client into your tool class**

```csharp
public class MyTool
{
    private readonly IMyApiClient _client;
    public MyTool(IMyApiClient client) => _client = client;

    public async Task<string> ExecuteAsync(string id)
    {
        var data = await _client.GetDataAsync(id);
        return data.Name;
    }
}
```

**3. Test project structure**

```
MyMcpServer.Tests/
├── MyMcpServer.Tests.csproj
├── Fakes/
│   └── FakeMyApiClient.cs      // or use Moq/NSubstitute
├── Tools/
│   └── MyToolTests.cs
└── Integration/
    └── McpServerTests.cs       // optional: test the full MCP pipeline
```

**4. Write tests with a fake or mock**

```csharp
// Using a simple fake
public class FakeMyApiClient : IMyApiClient
{
    public ResultDto Result { get; set; }
    public Task<ResultDto> GetDataAsync(string id) => Task.FromResult(Result);
}

// Test
[Fact]
public async Task ExecuteAsync_ReturnsName()
{
    var fake = new FakeMyApiClient { Result = new ResultDto { Name = "Test" } };
    var tool = new MyTool(fake);

    var result = await tool.ExecuteAsync("123");

    Assert.Equal("Test", result);
}
```

**Key packages to add:**

```xml
<ItemGroup>
  <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk" Version="17.*" />
  <PackageReference Include="xunit" Version="2.*" />
  <PackageReference Include="xunit.runner.visualstudio" Version="2.*" />
  <PackageReference Include="NSubstitute" Version="5.*" />  <!-- optional -->
</ItemGroup>
```

**Summary of the pattern:**

| Layer | Technique |
|-------|-----------|
| Unit tests | Mock/fake `IMyApiClient` |
| HTTP-level tests | Use `MockHttpMessageHandler` (from `RichardSzalay.MockHttp`) injected into a real `HttpClient` |
| Integration tests | Use `WebApplicationFactory` or spin up the MCP server with fakes registered in DI |

The critical principle: **inject `HttpClient` or an interface wrapper** so tests can substitute the real HTTP calls. If you're already using `IHttpClientFactory`, register a mock `HttpMessageHandler` in your test DI container.
